00:38:15.585 --> 00:38:17.210
That's why I told my
wife, don't worry,

00:38:17.210 --> 00:38:18.626
you're not married
to a short guy.

00:38:18.626 --> 00:38:22.220
You're married to an NBA star.

00:38:22.220 --> 00:38:27.350
Because the reality is that
your perceptual system gets

00:38:27.350 --> 00:38:31.860
tricked by this status cue.

00:38:31.860 --> 00:38:34.080
And so what happened here?

00:38:34.080 --> 00:38:39.660
This guy was judged as taller--

00:38:39.660 --> 00:38:42.990
there was what we called his
status elongation effect.

00:38:42.990 --> 00:38:47.330
He became taller, but
only in the eyes of whom?

00:38:47.330 --> 00:38:48.410
Women.

00:38:48.410 --> 00:38:51.170
What do you think
men rated the guy?

00:38:51.170 --> 00:38:52.520
Shorter.

00:38:52.520 --> 00:38:55.370
Which again speaks
to the psychology

00:38:55.370 --> 00:38:57.560
of intra-sexual rivalry.

00:38:57.560 --> 00:39:01.449
Both men and women
denigrate same-sex partners

00:39:01.449 --> 00:39:02.990
in a way that is
perfectly consistent

00:39:02.990 --> 00:39:04.198
with evolutionary principles.

00:39:04.198 --> 00:39:06.530
In this case, I am
threatened by a guy

00:39:06.530 --> 00:39:09.332
who may have higher status
than me, so I denigrate him.

00:39:09.332 --> 00:39:10.290
How do I denigrate him?

00:39:10.290 --> 00:39:13.310
Oh he's driving a Porsche, he
must be a little short runt.

00:39:13.310 --> 00:39:17.210
And so again, you see how
all of this psychology

00:39:17.210 --> 00:39:21.970
is playing into these basic
evolutionary principles.

00:39:21.970 --> 00:39:26.290
Very, very quickly let me do a
few more of these car studies.

00:39:26.290 --> 00:39:28.232
This is a study that was
done a long time ago.

00:39:28.232 --> 00:39:30.440
It might seem dated, but
it's actually very powerful,

00:39:30.440 --> 00:39:32.549
especially in
California, especially

00:39:32.549 --> 00:39:34.840
in a place like the Bay Area
here where a lot of people

00:39:34.840 --> 00:39:35.980
drive fancy cars.

00:39:35.980 --> 00:39:37.660
So here's what they
did in the study.

00:39:37.660 --> 00:39:39.576
At a red light-- this
was a field experiment--

00:39:39.576 --> 00:39:42.710
at a red light,
they actually put--

00:39:42.710 --> 00:39:44.860
these are the experimenters--
either a-- it wasn't

00:39:44.860 --> 00:39:49.360
these cars, this was
then 1968, so I just

00:39:49.360 --> 00:39:51.970
chose a fancy car
versus a non-fancy car.

00:39:51.970 --> 00:39:54.430
And they simply
looked at how long

00:39:54.430 --> 00:39:57.029
it took a person who
was-- wait, this person

00:39:57.029 --> 00:39:59.320
doesn't know that they're
going to be in an experiment.

00:39:59.320 --> 00:40:05.260
How many seconds when the
light turns from red to green

00:40:05.260 --> 00:40:07.990
do you exhibit
cues of impatience?

00:40:07.990 --> 00:40:11.170
Maybe you flick the
light, maybe you honk.

00:40:11.170 --> 00:40:13.870
Of course people were
a lot more impatient

00:40:13.870 --> 00:40:16.690
when the car that was blocking
them was lower status.

00:40:16.690 --> 00:40:20.320
That again speaks to certain
submissive dynamics that

00:40:20.320 --> 00:40:22.870
happen within social species.

00:40:22.870 --> 00:40:25.390
In this case, it's happening
in a very modern context

00:40:25.390 --> 00:40:28.248
in the way that we
respond on the road.

00:40:31.920 --> 00:40:36.890
In this case, in another
study almost 30 years later,

00:40:36.890 --> 00:40:41.260
they kept the status of the
car constant that's blocking.

00:40:41.260 --> 00:40:44.620
And then they looked at whether
the car that's being blocked

00:40:44.620 --> 00:40:47.950
would exhibit greater impatience
as a function of which car

00:40:47.950 --> 00:40:48.880
I was driving.

00:40:48.880 --> 00:40:51.160
If I am in a fancy
car, it'll take me

00:40:51.160 --> 00:40:53.500
less time to be irritated.

00:40:53.500 --> 00:40:55.420
And again, you could
see these types

00:40:55.420 --> 00:40:58.390
of dominance,
submission interactions

00:40:58.390 --> 00:41:02.070
across many social species.

00:41:02.070 --> 00:41:03.417
Let's move on.

00:41:03.417 --> 00:41:06.000
Now so far, a lot of the stuff
that I've been talking about it

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:10.530
seems as though I'm looking at
male-based sexual signaling.

00:41:10.530 --> 00:41:12.280
But of course, that's not true.

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:14.610
Women-- I mean in the
human context, and not

00:41:14.610 --> 00:41:17.310
just human context,
but across animals.

00:41:17.310 --> 00:41:21.400
Women, of course-- or females,
in the greater context--

00:41:21.400 --> 00:41:22.850
will engage in sexual signaling.

00:41:22.850 --> 00:41:27.820
So in this case, this
is a female chimp.

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:30.100
She will exhibit estrus--

00:41:30.100 --> 00:41:32.230
that she is in a sexually
receptive state--

00:41:32.230 --> 00:41:34.300
by sending certain
olfactory signals

00:41:34.300 --> 00:41:35.950
that are very
attractive to the males.

00:41:35.950 --> 00:41:39.910
Her genitalia will become
engorged, will become enlarged.

00:41:39.910 --> 00:41:42.910
And this is basically saying
that she is sexually receptive.

00:41:42.910 --> 00:41:44.620
So I took this idea
and I thought, well,

00:41:44.620 --> 00:41:47.290
how could we apply this
principle, which manifests

00:41:47.290 --> 00:41:51.550
itself across many, many
species to the human context

00:41:51.550 --> 00:41:53.950
and, specifically, to
the consumer context.

00:41:53.950 --> 00:41:56.860
And the idea was to
look at how women

00:41:56.860 --> 00:42:00.100
dress as a function
of where they

00:42:00.100 --> 00:42:03.060
are in their ovulatory cycle.

00:42:03.060 --> 00:42:04.740
And what do you think we found?

00:42:04.740 --> 00:42:07.830
When women are in the
maximum fertile stage

00:42:07.830 --> 00:42:09.240
of their menstrual cycle--

00:42:09.240 --> 00:42:12.450
when they're ovulating--
they dress more sexily.

00:42:12.450 --> 00:42:13.920
They beautify more.

00:42:13.920 --> 00:42:15.690
Now that doesn't
mean, by the way,

00:42:15.690 --> 00:42:18.550
that they look at an ovulation
chart and say, oh geez,

00:42:18.550 --> 00:42:20.920
OK, there's ovulation, let
me dress with shorter skirt.

00:42:20.920 --> 00:42:23.970
It's a subconscious mechanism.

00:42:23.970 --> 00:42:25.830
I feel more sexy.

00:42:25.830 --> 00:42:26.910
I feel less bloated.

00:42:26.910 --> 00:42:28.400
I feel more desirable.

00:42:28.400 --> 00:42:30.330
My self-esteem is higher.

00:42:30.330 --> 00:42:34.110
And so all of these
mechanisms ensure

00:42:34.110 --> 00:42:37.560
that a woman is more likely to
advertise herself in the mating

00:42:37.560 --> 00:42:39.810
market when,
evolutionarily speaking,

00:42:39.810 --> 00:42:42.790
it makes more sense to do so.

00:42:42.790 --> 00:42:45.060
Now these studies are
unassailable because they're

00:42:45.060 --> 00:42:48.000
looking at very
basic physiological,

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:50.250
hormonal, biological facts.

00:42:50.250 --> 00:42:52.770
That's why I very
carefully selected

00:42:52.770 --> 00:42:55.810
to do these studies because
it makes them a lot more

00:42:55.810 --> 00:42:58.410
difficult for my social science
colleagues to say, oh yeah,

00:42:58.410 --> 00:42:59.940
but this is just
due to learning.

00:42:59.940 --> 00:43:01.980
This is just due to culture.

00:43:01.980 --> 00:43:06.225
Because they're so basic in
their physiological genesis.

00:43:08.892 --> 00:43:09.600
Let's keep going.

00:43:13.120 --> 00:43:15.970
Switching gears.

00:43:15.970 --> 00:43:20.120
At the end of a successful
mating encounter,

00:43:20.120 --> 00:43:21.790
you might have a
child and so this

00:43:21.790 --> 00:43:23.290
is kind of the segue to this.

00:43:23.290 --> 00:43:29.230
Here's a study that was done in
Mexico in the Yucatan region.

00:43:29.230 --> 00:43:34.310
When a baby was born,
people would say, oh my god,

00:43:34.310 --> 00:43:37.750
he looks so much
like the father,

00:43:37.750 --> 00:43:42.400
even though objectively
that's absolutely untrue.

00:43:42.400 --> 00:43:45.140
That's absolutely untrue in
that the morphological features

00:43:45.140 --> 00:43:49.580
of a newborn haven't yet
sufficiently formed for you

00:43:49.580 --> 00:43:52.670
to be able to objectively
he looks more like the dad

00:43:52.670 --> 00:43:55.790
or he looks more like the mom.

00:43:55.790 --> 00:43:57.590
So something's going on.

00:43:57.590 --> 00:44:01.100
Not only do people
say, oh my god,

00:44:01.100 --> 00:44:04.400
he looks so much
like his father,

00:44:04.400 --> 00:44:08.750
but which side of the family
is more likely to say it?

00:44:08.750 --> 00:44:11.966
The mother's side because
the mother's side,

00:44:11.966 --> 00:44:13.340
from an evolutionary
perspective,

00:44:13.340 --> 00:44:17.660
wants to send a very clear
signal to the father that don't

00:44:17.660 --> 00:44:19.910
worry, this is your child.

00:44:19.910 --> 00:44:22.760
So before we had
DNA paternity tests

00:44:22.760 --> 00:44:26.660
and before we had the
Maury Povich show, where

00:44:26.660 --> 00:44:29.540
every second episode
is exactly that,

00:44:29.540 --> 00:44:32.780
we had to come up with
a cultural mechanism

00:44:32.780 --> 00:44:35.240
to ensure paternity certainty.

00:44:35.240 --> 00:44:38.840
And the way we do that is
by fakely stating, my god,

00:44:38.840 --> 00:44:42.110
he looks exactly like you.

00:44:42.110 --> 00:44:44.730
And by the way, if
you're wondering

00:44:44.730 --> 00:44:49.650
why these two gorgeous,
stunning kids are so gorgeous,

00:44:49.650 --> 00:44:52.760
that's because those
are my children.

00:44:52.760 --> 00:44:55.950
This is Luna when she was
very young, and this is Leor.

00:44:55.950 --> 00:44:57.516
They're now a bit older.

00:44:57.516 --> 00:44:59.390
They're in Southern
California waiting for me

00:44:59.390 --> 00:45:00.181
to go to the beach.

00:45:00.181 --> 00:45:02.360
I am from the beach to
come to Google and speak.

00:45:05.210 --> 00:45:07.760
Now I want to tell you
a little fun story.

00:45:07.760 --> 00:45:09.710
I mentioned this story
before, but I always

00:45:09.710 --> 00:45:12.110
love repeating it
because it demonstrates

00:45:12.110 --> 00:45:14.840
the power of
evolutionary thinking

00:45:14.840 --> 00:45:16.670
in understanding
our daily lives.

00:45:22.180 --> 00:45:30.670
These are the actual images, the
first images of Luna in utero.

00:45:30.670 --> 00:45:33.120
So for those of you
who are parents,

00:45:33.120 --> 00:45:38.280
you know that when the mother
goes the first time to OBGYN,

00:45:38.280 --> 00:45:40.480
usually you get those images.

00:45:40.480 --> 00:45:42.060
Most people are very
happy and proud.

00:45:42.060 --> 00:45:43.140
They celebrate this.

00:45:43.140 --> 00:45:45.120
They'll put it up on the fridge.

00:45:45.120 --> 00:45:46.180
We were no different.

00:45:46.180 --> 00:45:51.030
We put up this image and one
day my mother-in-law comes over

00:45:51.030 --> 00:45:52.639
to our house, looks at--

00:45:52.639 --> 00:45:54.180
some people are
laughing because they

00:45:54.180 --> 00:45:55.830
know where I'm going with this.

00:45:55.830 --> 00:45:58.920
She looks and she goes, oh
my god, Gad, the baby looks

00:45:58.920 --> 00:45:59.850
exactly like you.

00:46:02.910 --> 00:46:05.340
So I made my daughter
famous because this

00:46:05.340 --> 00:46:08.220
was the first case
in science where

00:46:08.220 --> 00:46:10.620
the maternal side
of the family was

00:46:10.620 --> 00:46:16.180
trying to assure a father of
paternity certainty in utero.

00:46:16.180 --> 00:46:18.480
So I said, should I
be worried that you're

00:46:18.480 --> 00:46:23.430
trying so hard to convince
me that your daughter didn't

00:46:23.430 --> 00:46:25.122
go behind the bushes on me?

00:46:25.122 --> 00:46:26.580
She looks at me
she goes, oh enough

00:46:26.580 --> 00:46:27.954
with your bullshit
science stuff.

00:46:27.954 --> 00:46:28.710
Look at that.

00:46:28.710 --> 00:46:30.954
She looks exactly like you.

00:46:30.954 --> 00:46:33.120
Oh actually, she didn't
know it was a she because we

00:46:33.120 --> 00:46:34.440
didn't know what sex it was--

00:46:34.440 --> 00:46:35.550
it looks exactly like you.

00:46:39.120 --> 00:46:43.330
Here's a study that was actually
just accepted for publication.

00:46:43.330 --> 00:46:44.550
This is Sigal Tifferet.

00:46:44.550 --> 00:46:47.830
This is myself and two other
young folks who helped us out.

00:46:47.830 --> 00:46:50.430
This is actually the
photo of my parents

00:46:50.430 --> 00:46:52.680
when they got married in 1950.

00:46:52.680 --> 00:46:55.930
They're still both alive.

00:46:55.930 --> 00:46:57.680
This was a study
where we looked at--

00:46:57.680 --> 00:46:59.930
that this is going to speak
about paternity certainty.

00:46:59.930 --> 00:47:01.346
So you might say,
how do you apply

00:47:01.346 --> 00:47:02.440
this in consumer behavior?

00:47:02.440 --> 00:47:05.000
Watch.

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:11.300
The data here is from Israeli
weddings where this author

00:47:11.300 --> 00:47:12.800
along with these guys--

00:47:12.800 --> 00:47:14.750
they asked me to
come in on the paper

00:47:14.750 --> 00:47:17.000
to help with the
evolutionary story.

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:21.200
And this paper by the way is the
longest, most circuitous paper

00:47:21.200 --> 00:47:24.260
that I've ever had in my
scientific career before it

00:47:24.260 --> 00:47:25.940
being accepted for publication.

00:47:25.940 --> 00:47:29.300
We've worked on this paper I
think for more than five years

00:47:29.300 --> 00:47:31.820
after the peer review process.

00:47:31.820 --> 00:47:35.120
That's how long it took to get
this paper through for reasons

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:38.930
related to people's antipathy
towards biological-based

00:47:38.930 --> 00:47:39.830
thinking.

00:47:39.830 --> 00:47:42.600
So let me explain to you
what we did in this paper.

00:47:42.600 --> 00:47:46.280
We had data from 30
actual Israeli weddings--

00:47:46.280 --> 00:47:48.440
Excel sheets--
where every person

00:47:48.440 --> 00:47:52.580
who attended the wedding, we
had how much money they gave.

00:47:52.580 --> 00:47:54.380
So in other words, in
the Israeli context,

00:47:54.380 --> 00:47:58.220
you don't give toasters and
whatever other appliances.

00:47:58.220 --> 00:47:59.360
You just give money.

00:47:59.360 --> 00:48:05.210
So Uncle Mordecai,
$180, Aunt Hannah, $200.

00:48:05.210 --> 00:48:09.522
And so we had all this data,
and so we tested two things.

00:48:09.522 --> 00:48:11.480
One of them is pretty
obvious for you to guess,

00:48:11.480 --> 00:48:13.620
the other one is not so obvious.

00:48:13.620 --> 00:48:16.340
The first thing we
looked at is the size

00:48:16.340 --> 00:48:18.530
of the wedding
gift as a function

00:48:18.530 --> 00:48:23.150
of the genetic relatedness
between the giver and the bride

00:48:23.150 --> 00:48:23.700
and groom.

00:48:23.700 --> 00:48:25.220
And what do you think happens?

00:48:25.220 --> 00:48:27.170
To the greater the
genetic relatedness,

00:48:27.170 --> 00:48:29.300
the larger the gift.

00:48:29.300 --> 00:48:32.360
In other words, people
modulate their investment

00:48:32.360 --> 00:48:37.996
in others as a function
of the genetic lineage.

00:48:37.996 --> 00:48:39.870
Now you might say, well
I could have probably

00:48:39.870 --> 00:48:43.140
predicted this without being a
fancy evolutionary scientist.

00:48:43.140 --> 00:48:44.940
The second hypothesis
you couldn't.

00:48:44.940 --> 00:48:46.080
Here it goes.

00:48:46.080 --> 00:48:50.650
If you take, for example, your
four grandparents, on average,

00:48:50.650 --> 00:48:51.670
they share--

00:48:51.670 --> 00:48:54.100
each of them-- a quarter
of their genes with you.

00:48:54.100 --> 00:48:57.080
In other words, the
genetic relatedness is 25%.

00:48:57.080 --> 00:48:59.140
If you stop the
story there, they're

00:48:59.140 --> 00:49:00.920
all equally invested in you.

00:49:00.920 --> 00:49:03.350
But there is a second
element to the story.

00:49:03.350 --> 00:49:05.470
It's not just
genetic relatedness,

00:49:05.470 --> 00:49:08.020
it's genetic assuredness.

00:49:08.020 --> 00:49:10.930
How assured are you
of a genetic lineage?

00:49:10.930 --> 00:49:15.880
Well, your maternal grandmother
is assured of her lineage.

00:49:15.880 --> 00:49:19.970
There is no such thing
as maternity uncertainty.

00:49:19.970 --> 00:49:24.160
Your paternal grandfather
has two generations

00:49:24.160 --> 00:49:25.900
of paternity uncertainty.

00:49:25.900 --> 00:49:28.030
Therefore, we expect
the maternal grandmother

00:49:28.030 --> 00:49:30.580
to invest the most, the
paternal grandfather

00:49:30.580 --> 00:49:32.950
to invest the least, and
the two other grandparents

00:49:32.950 --> 00:49:33.950
in the middle.

00:49:33.950 --> 00:49:35.650
So we took this--

00:49:35.650 --> 00:49:39.310
the fancy term is differential
solicitude-- we took this idea

00:49:39.310 --> 00:49:42.270
and applied it in
the following way.

00:49:42.270 --> 00:49:45.480
Does the matrilineal side
of the bride and groom

00:49:45.480 --> 00:49:48.900
give larger gifts than
the patrilineal side?

00:49:48.900 --> 00:49:49.920
And the answer is yes.

00:49:49.920 --> 00:49:51.690
This is the one for matrilineal.

00:49:51.690 --> 00:49:53.700
This is the one for patrilineal.

00:49:53.700 --> 00:49:56.820
So holding genetic
relatedness constant,

00:49:56.820 --> 00:49:58.590
when you come from
the mother's side,

00:49:58.590 --> 00:50:02.010
you give greater gifts than when
you do from the fathers side.

00:50:02.010 --> 00:50:04.500
No one would have
generated this hypothesis

00:50:04.500 --> 00:50:06.600
if you weren't coming
from an evolutionary lens.

00:50:06.600 --> 00:50:09.360
You couldn't have even
posited that hypothesis.

00:50:12.914 --> 00:50:14.580
I don't want to spend
much time on this.

00:50:14.580 --> 00:50:17.240
But remember earlier I talked
about that conciliar tree

00:50:17.240 --> 00:50:18.120
of knowledge?

00:50:18.120 --> 00:50:20.249
This is exactly an example
of a consilient tree

00:50:20.249 --> 00:50:21.790
when it comes to
evolutionary theory.

00:50:21.790 --> 00:50:25.100
You start with some general
evolutionary principles

00:50:25.100 --> 00:50:26.310
that are now unassailable.

00:50:26.310 --> 00:50:28.700
They've been tested
for over 150 years.

00:50:28.700 --> 00:50:32.150
These lead to what are
called middle level theories.

00:50:32.150 --> 00:50:33.860
Kin selection is
the mechanism that

00:50:33.860 --> 00:50:37.580
explains why people or
animals invest in their kin

00:50:37.580 --> 00:50:40.250
more so than in
random strangers.

00:50:40.250 --> 00:50:43.640
Based on kin selection, I
could generate hypotheses

00:50:43.640 --> 00:50:45.980
about genetic relatedness
and genetic assuredness,

00:50:45.980 --> 00:50:48.080
and then based on
that, I just told you

00:50:48.080 --> 00:50:50.000
the study that I mentioned.

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:52.760
Therefore, what
evolutionary theory does

00:50:52.760 --> 00:50:56.120
is it provides you with these
elegant, organized trees

00:50:56.120 --> 00:50:58.790
of knowledge, very much like
you would expect in physics

00:50:58.790 --> 00:51:00.510
and chemistry and biology.

00:51:00.510 --> 00:51:02.600
And so one of the arguments
that I make and some

00:51:02.600 --> 00:51:04.820
of my evolutionary
minded colleagues make

00:51:04.820 --> 00:51:07.610
is that the social
sciences will eventually

00:51:07.610 --> 00:51:11.210
have to go through the same
revolution that biology did.

00:51:11.210 --> 00:51:15.680
To date, no working biologist
says that evolutionary theory

00:51:15.680 --> 00:51:18.150
is maybe right, maybe wrong.

00:51:18.150 --> 00:51:21.110
There is no chemistry
professor who

00:51:21.110 --> 00:51:23.780
is for the periodic
table and some

00:51:23.780 --> 00:51:26.390
who are anti-periodic table.

00:51:26.390 --> 00:51:28.610
The same thing has to happen
in the social sciences.

00:51:28.610 --> 00:51:31.670
For us to have the same
impact and same influence,

00:51:31.670 --> 00:51:34.640
we have to agree that there
is a set of core knowledge

00:51:34.640 --> 00:51:36.440
that after awhile
becomes unassailable.

00:51:36.440 --> 00:51:39.620
And the way you do that is by
building these coherent trees

00:51:39.620 --> 00:51:41.120
of knowledge.

00:51:41.120 --> 00:51:43.672
All right we're almost done.

00:51:43.672 --> 00:51:45.880
Let me just read you a few
quotes that are very, very

00:51:45.880 --> 00:51:47.710
powerful to really
drive the point

00:51:47.710 --> 00:51:49.489
home of the
importance of biology

00:51:49.489 --> 00:51:50.530
to everything that we do.

00:51:50.530 --> 00:51:53.330
This is an exchange that
took place on Charlie Rose.

00:51:53.330 --> 00:51:56.110
If any of you watch it,it's
usually late at night on PBS.

00:51:56.110 --> 00:51:59.229
He brings all sorts of guests
and they get into a really fun

00:51:59.229 --> 00:51:59.770
conversation.

00:51:59.770 --> 00:52:03.220
This is EO Wilson, who's
a very famous Harvard

00:52:03.220 --> 00:52:04.910
entomologist still alive.

00:52:04.910 --> 00:52:07.400
One of the biggest scientists
of the 20th century.

00:52:07.400 --> 00:52:11.020
This is James Watson,
the co-discoverer

00:52:11.020 --> 00:52:15.910
of the double helix structure
of DNA, Nobel Prize winner.

00:52:15.910 --> 00:52:17.750
And they're talking
to each other.

00:52:17.750 --> 00:52:18.600
So let me just read it for you.

00:52:18.600 --> 00:52:20.590
"Psychologist, most of the
practicing psychologists

00:52:20.590 --> 00:52:22.715
and theoretical psychologists
and the vast majority

00:52:22.715 --> 00:52:24.520
of social sciences,
who really determine

00:52:24.520 --> 00:52:26.380
a lot of the intellect that
goes into our policies,

00:52:26.380 --> 00:52:28.480
you know, and our
philosophies, our philosophies,

00:52:28.480 --> 00:52:31.450
have no collection at all to
their true nature of humanity

00:52:31.450 --> 00:52:34.840
or what human nature is
at a biological level.

00:52:34.840 --> 00:52:36.234
This is still a huge gap.

00:52:36.234 --> 00:52:37.900
And I believe that
we will start to fill

00:52:37.900 --> 00:52:40.780
that in a way that
will be useful in years

00:52:40.780 --> 00:52:42.310
immediately ahead.

00:52:42.310 --> 00:52:44.860
I see the coming-- the past
century was the coming together

00:52:44.860 --> 00:52:46.160
of chemistry and biology.

00:52:46.160 --> 00:52:48.760
This century will be the
coming together of psychology

00:52:48.760 --> 00:52:51.370
and biology. " This is
exactly what I do in my work.

00:52:51.370 --> 00:52:54.680
I marry psychology and biology.

00:52:54.680 --> 00:52:57.670
Now interestingly-- this might
interest some of the folks here

00:52:57.670 --> 00:52:59.860
who are more
practitioner-oriented--

00:52:59.860 --> 00:53:04.780
practitioners of business
are typically a lot less--

00:53:04.780 --> 00:53:08.650
they exhibit a lot less animus
to these ideas than academics.

00:53:08.650 --> 00:53:12.340
Because academics are typically
vested within their paradigms

00:53:12.340 --> 00:53:15.640
and therefore, if you come
along on your biology horse

00:53:15.640 --> 00:53:17.382
and if they feel
threatened, then they

00:53:17.382 --> 00:53:18.340
will put up resistance.

00:53:18.340 --> 00:53:20.280
Well, the practitioner
doesn't care.

00:53:20.280 --> 00:53:22.600
The practitioner simply
cares about what works.

00:53:22.600 --> 00:53:25.660
So if you're an advertising
executive and my theories can

00:53:25.660 --> 00:53:29.360
help you develop better
advertising appeals, go for it.

00:53:29.360 --> 00:53:32.650
And so here's an example
from way back in 1964.

00:53:32.650 --> 00:53:35.290
This could have been written by
an evolutionary psychologist.

00:53:35.290 --> 00:53:36.460
Let me just read it for you.

00:53:36.460 --> 00:53:38.770
"Because advertising,
effective advertising,

00:53:38.770 --> 00:53:42.500
is an appeal to human
fundamental needs, desires,

00:53:42.500 --> 00:53:45.220
and motivations, it is an
appeal to basic human nature.

00:53:45.220 --> 00:53:47.410
People the world over
have the same basic need

00:53:47.410 --> 00:53:49.780
for food, clothing, and
shelter, the same ambitions,

00:53:49.780 --> 00:53:52.090
the same egotism, and
the same temptations.

00:53:52.090 --> 00:53:54.220
The setting changes, the
climate, the culture,

00:53:54.220 --> 00:53:57.730
the idiom, but the basic
human nature is the same. "

00:53:57.730 --> 00:53:59.480
This is basically
evolutionary psychology.

00:53:59.480 --> 00:54:01.570
It's looking at these
human universals.

00:54:01.570 --> 00:54:04.312
And then this one is
the founder of one

00:54:04.312 --> 00:54:06.520
of the biggest advertising
firms of the 20th century.

00:54:06.520 --> 00:54:07.895
He's basically
saying if you want

00:54:07.895 --> 00:54:09.280
to understand how
to communicate,

00:54:09.280 --> 00:54:10.780
you have to understand
human nature.

00:54:10.780 --> 00:54:14.885
Again, this is very much
of a evolutionary argument.

00:54:14.885 --> 00:54:15.795
Almost done.

00:54:18.530 --> 00:54:21.380
Before I put up--

00:54:21.380 --> 00:54:22.792
let me just--

00:54:22.792 --> 00:54:24.750
Sometimes I get people
who would say, well, OK,

00:54:24.750 --> 00:54:27.770
but give me some very clear,
practical applications

00:54:27.770 --> 00:54:30.320
of the fancy
scientific work you do.

00:54:30.320 --> 00:54:32.600
Well here's one, which
will be the next slide.

00:54:32.600 --> 00:54:36.380
If good marketers, whether
they know it or not,

00:54:36.380 --> 00:54:38.450
understand human nature well.

00:54:38.450 --> 00:54:42.020
If you develop products
that are contrary

00:54:42.020 --> 00:54:45.240
to some basic principle
from human nature,

00:54:45.240 --> 00:54:47.270
the product will fail.

00:54:47.270 --> 00:54:51.800
So for example, McDonald
works well not so much

00:54:51.800 --> 00:54:55.430
because it gets celebrity
endorsers to support it,

00:54:55.430 --> 00:54:57.590
but it's because it
offers you a product

00:54:57.590 --> 00:55:01.160
that my evolved gustatory
preferences expect.

00:55:01.160 --> 00:55:03.170
Give me fatty, tasty foods.

00:55:03.170 --> 00:55:06.230
Well it's not difficult to teach
most children around the world

00:55:06.230 --> 00:55:08.780
to like that product
because, again, as I said,

00:55:08.780 --> 00:55:11.990
our taste buds have
evolved to like

00:55:11.990 --> 00:55:14.150
that because of the
environment of caloric scarcity

00:55:14.150 --> 00:55:16.500
and caloric uncertainty
that we've evolved in.

00:55:16.500 --> 00:55:19.490
So here's an example
that speaks to this idea.

00:55:19.490 --> 00:55:23.480
Romance novels are
almost exclusively

00:55:23.480 --> 00:55:26.390
read around the
world only by women.

00:55:26.390 --> 00:55:27.775
There is no culture.

00:55:27.775 --> 00:55:29.900
And if you can find that
culture, send me an email,

00:55:29.900 --> 00:55:31.280
I'll make you famous.

00:55:31.280 --> 00:55:33.300
You won't find it
because it doesn't exist.

00:55:33.300 --> 00:55:37.040
There is no culture where men
are the predominant consumers

00:55:37.040 --> 00:55:38.580
of romance novels.

00:55:38.580 --> 00:55:40.490
Now you might say, OK, so what?

00:55:40.490 --> 00:55:45.020
Well, if you want to
understand female sexuality,

00:55:45.020 --> 00:55:50.360
study the archetype of the
male hero in romance novels.

00:55:50.360 --> 00:55:51.560
It is the exact same guy.

00:55:51.560 --> 00:55:55.642
It's a cut and paste job
irrespective of which country--

00:55:55.642 --> 00:55:56.850
and very different countries.

00:55:56.850 --> 00:55:58.310
It can be Pakistan.

00:55:58.310 --> 00:55:59.960
It could be Lebanon.

00:55:59.960 --> 00:56:00.890
It could be Bolivia.

00:56:00.890 --> 00:56:02.570
It could be Japan.

00:56:02.570 --> 00:56:04.640
The male hero is
the exact same guy.

00:56:04.640 --> 00:56:05.900
He's tall.

00:56:05.900 --> 00:56:08.450
He's a prince and
a neurosurgeon.

00:56:08.450 --> 00:56:14.390
He wrangles alligators
on his six pack.

00:56:14.390 --> 00:56:17.630
He's reckless in
his risk-taking,

00:56:17.630 --> 00:56:20.210
but he could only be tamed
by the love of this one

00:56:20.210 --> 00:56:21.105
good woman.

00:56:21.105 --> 00:56:25.730
Boom, I just read for you
every single romance novel.

00:56:25.730 --> 00:56:31.350
Not surprisingly, every
single cover the guy

00:56:31.350 --> 00:56:32.940
looks exactly the same.

00:56:32.940 --> 00:56:36.040
He never looks like this guy.

00:56:36.040 --> 00:56:36.870
Who?

00:56:36.870 --> 00:56:41.100
Is this is this
some VP of Google?

00:56:41.100 --> 00:56:44.640
I shall never be
invited again here.

00:56:44.640 --> 00:56:49.020
So this is not because
there is a conspiracy

00:56:49.020 --> 00:56:53.970
to promulgate unrealistic
images of masculinity.

00:56:53.970 --> 00:56:57.720
It's because marketers
understand what, in this case,

00:56:57.720 --> 00:57:00.750
appeals to women's
evolved fantasies,

00:57:00.750 --> 00:57:03.210
and they provide a product
that is consistent with that.

00:57:03.210 --> 00:57:04.170
There was a company--

00:57:04.170 --> 00:57:05.711
I don't remember
what it was called--

00:57:05.711 --> 00:57:07.470
that tried to move
away from that.

00:57:07.470 --> 00:57:11.580
They wanted to create a
new line of romance novels

00:57:11.580 --> 00:57:14.400
that broke the shackles of this.

00:57:14.400 --> 00:57:16.820
Guess what happened
to that company?

00:57:16.820 --> 00:57:18.250
It died.

00:57:18.250 --> 00:57:23.520
It died because it had an
erroneous view of human nature.

00:57:23.520 --> 00:57:26.580
It thought that human nature
is infinitely malleable

00:57:26.580 --> 00:57:30.395
when human nature is
constrained by biology.

00:57:32.940 --> 00:57:33.770
So I'm almost done.

00:57:33.770 --> 00:57:35.390
I think maybe two more slides.

00:57:35.390 --> 00:57:39.330
This quote right
here, I've always

00:57:39.330 --> 00:57:41.280
joked that if I ever
wrote an autobiography

00:57:41.280 --> 00:57:43.980
of my scientific life, it
would consist of one page.

00:57:43.980 --> 00:57:45.480
Basically, this quote.

00:57:45.480 --> 00:57:46.140
Why?

00:57:46.140 --> 00:57:49.050
Because this quote
perfectly captures

00:57:49.050 --> 00:57:50.880
what I have faced in
my scientific career.

00:57:50.880 --> 00:57:53.850
This is JBS Haldane,
who is a very famous

00:57:53.850 --> 00:57:57.060
evolutionary geneticist and also
a guy kind of like Mark Twain.

00:57:57.060 --> 00:58:01.470
He had this beautiful ability
with words, great quips.

00:58:01.470 --> 00:58:04.620
He said, when scientists
go through a new radical

00:58:04.620 --> 00:58:09.344
scientific idea, they go through
four stages of acceptance.

00:58:09.344 --> 00:58:11.760
When they first hear about it,
this is worthless nonsense.

00:58:11.760 --> 00:58:12.930
This is garbage.

00:58:12.930 --> 00:58:15.652
In my case, you're applying
biology to consumer behavior?

00:58:15.652 --> 00:58:16.860
What kind of heretic are you?

00:58:16.860 --> 00:58:18.500
You're a moron.

00:58:18.500 --> 00:58:22.020
Stage 2, as the evidence
starts coming in,

00:58:22.020 --> 00:58:26.850
well, this is interesting, but
it's a perverse point of view.

00:58:26.850 --> 00:58:30.300
Stage 3, this is
true, but who cares.

00:58:30.300 --> 00:58:31.440
Quite unimportant.

00:58:31.440 --> 00:58:34.600
Stage for, when the
paradigmatic wall breaks,

00:58:34.600 --> 00:58:35.610
oh, I've always said so.

00:58:35.610 --> 00:58:38.520
I've always loved
your work, Dr. Saad.

00:58:38.520 --> 00:58:40.380
I still have emails--

00:58:40.380 --> 00:58:43.630
and I say this with
all due modesty--

00:58:43.630 --> 00:58:47.400
I still have emails from
guys who had written to me

00:58:47.400 --> 00:58:50.250
when they were at stage
one, but they don't

00:58:50.250 --> 00:58:51.890
know that I've kept that email.

00:58:51.890 --> 00:58:53.970
Now they're writing
to me at stage 4,

00:58:53.970 --> 00:58:55.560
will you do us the honor?

00:58:55.560 --> 00:58:57.300
But I thought I was
a bullshitter who

00:58:57.300 --> 00:58:59.370
applied biology.

00:58:59.370 --> 00:59:01.350
Because that's
how science works.

00:59:01.350 --> 00:59:03.090
It's an auto-corrective process.

00:59:03.090 --> 00:59:06.780
Hopefully, the good
ideas eventually win out.

00:59:06.780 --> 00:59:08.370
And were almost done.

00:59:08.370 --> 00:59:10.890
Last slide.

00:59:10.890 --> 00:59:14.460
Dobzhansky famously
stated, "nothing in biology

00:59:14.460 --> 00:59:16.872
makes sense except in
the light of evolution."

00:59:16.872 --> 00:59:19.080
And if you walk away with
nothing other than this one

00:59:19.080 --> 00:59:21.300
quote, I slightly
tweak this to say,

00:59:21.300 --> 00:59:23.280
nothing in consumer
behavior or in business

00:59:23.280 --> 00:59:25.740
makes sense except in
the light of evolution.

