knowledge to protect oneself

01:04:58.590 --> 01:05:02.790
from step-mothers, advertisers
and mother in-laws and things

01:05:02.790 --> 01:05:03.610
like that?

01:05:03.610 --> 01:05:05.485
GAD SAAD: Well, I mean
it's a broad question.

01:05:05.485 --> 01:05:07.050
I think to use a cliche--

01:05:07.050 --> 01:05:08.620
knowledge is power.

01:05:08.620 --> 01:05:13.290
So to the extent that each of
us has a key-- in this case,

01:05:13.290 --> 01:05:15.060
evolutionary
psychology-- to help us

01:05:15.060 --> 01:05:18.270
understand human behavior,
then it's a very powerful thing

01:05:18.270 --> 01:05:19.230
to have.

01:05:19.230 --> 01:05:23.610
I will get students who took
my course 10 years earlier who

01:05:23.610 --> 01:05:27.030
will write to me and
say, hi professor Saad,

01:05:27.030 --> 01:05:28.740
I remember the lecture
where you talked

01:05:28.740 --> 01:05:33.360
about the evolutionary
roots of romantic jealousy,

01:05:33.360 --> 01:05:36.069
and I'm currently having such
and such fight with my wife

01:05:36.069 --> 01:05:37.110
because of such and such.

01:05:37.110 --> 01:05:39.060
And it perfectly
matches what you are--

01:05:39.060 --> 01:05:41.570
So in other words, it's
not as though there

01:05:41.570 --> 01:05:43.350
is a prescription
for every syllable

01:05:43.350 --> 01:05:45.810
that I utter to a specific
practical application,

01:05:45.810 --> 01:05:47.990
but rather, having
that knowledge,

01:05:47.990 --> 01:05:49.740
allows us to better
understand everything.

01:05:49.740 --> 01:05:52.770
It allows us to understand
group dynamics of Google

01:05:52.770 --> 01:05:55.650
and why I'm going to fight
for the corner office

01:05:55.650 --> 01:05:58.330
because it serves
as a status symbol.

01:05:58.330 --> 01:06:00.780
So in other words, I'm
giving you a universal key

01:06:00.780 --> 01:06:02.230
for understanding human nature.

01:06:02.230 --> 01:06:02.970
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

01:06:02.970 --> 01:06:04.975
GAD SAAD: Cheers.

01:06:04.975 --> 01:06:06.350
AUDIENCE: First
of all, thank you

01:06:06.350 --> 01:06:07.870
so much for giving this talk.

01:06:07.870 --> 01:06:08.870
It was very interesting.

01:06:08.870 --> 01:06:09.470
GAD SAAD: Thank you.

01:06:09.470 --> 01:06:11.150
AUDIENCE: I want to ask you
about one of the studies

01:06:11.150 --> 01:06:13.010
that you talked about--
the wedding gifts.

01:06:13.010 --> 01:06:14.010
GAD SAAD: Yes.

01:06:14.010 --> 01:06:16.010
AUDIENCE: My question is,
how do you come from--

01:06:16.010 --> 01:06:17.843
the data that you've
collected-- how did you

01:06:17.843 --> 01:06:19.140
come to a certain conclusion?

01:06:19.140 --> 01:06:22.460
For example, in Lebanon,
I grew up there.

01:06:22.460 --> 01:06:25.940
You know if my granddaughter
were to get married,

01:06:25.940 --> 01:06:27.960
my granddaughter is more
valuable to the family.

01:06:27.960 --> 01:06:30.050
So typically, families
give more gifts

01:06:30.050 --> 01:06:33.532
to the female that's getting
married than the guy.

01:06:33.532 --> 01:06:34.490
That might be a reason.

01:06:34.490 --> 01:06:35.660
There might be other reasons.

01:06:35.660 --> 01:06:37.035
How do you come
to the conclusion

01:06:37.035 --> 01:06:41.332
that it's an evolutionary
thing not something else?

01:06:41.332 --> 01:06:43.040
GAD SAAD: So several
ways to answer that.

01:06:43.040 --> 01:06:46.400
One is that, as is the
case in all science,

01:06:46.400 --> 01:06:49.460
you have to rule out
alternate explanations.

01:06:49.460 --> 01:06:51.770
If you can't rule out an
alternate explanations.

01:06:51.770 --> 01:06:53.630
Then your data is
not as convincing

01:06:53.630 --> 01:06:55.334
as it otherwise could be.

01:06:55.334 --> 01:06:56.750
But I also showed
you how we build

01:06:56.750 --> 01:06:58.370
these nomological networks.

01:06:58.370 --> 01:07:02.270
These nomological networks,
not one of the boxes

01:07:02.270 --> 01:07:05.250
is enough to convince you,
but once I show you the eight

01:07:05.250 --> 01:07:07.280
boxes, it becomes
difficult for you

01:07:07.280 --> 01:07:08.930
to argue against my position.

01:07:08.930 --> 01:07:11.340
So that's how you do
it in evolution theory.

01:07:11.340 --> 01:07:13.730
You accumulate
evidence stemming from

01:07:13.730 --> 01:07:16.760
many, many different
regions, many different lines

01:07:16.760 --> 01:07:18.440
of evidence, that it
makes it impossible

01:07:18.440 --> 01:07:20.990
for you to generate an
alternative explanation

01:07:20.990 --> 01:07:22.822
to explain the phenomenon.

01:07:22.822 --> 01:07:23.734
Thank you.

01:07:25.995 --> 01:07:27.870
AUDIENCE: Thank you so
much for coming today.

01:07:27.870 --> 01:07:28.230
GAD SAAD: Thank you.

01:07:28.230 --> 01:07:30.646
AUDIENCE: It's been amazing
to hear your presentation live

01:07:30.646 --> 01:07:32.450
and not just on podcast.

01:07:32.450 --> 01:07:34.330
Second, my question
is, through the lens

01:07:34.330 --> 01:07:37.990
of evolutionary biology,
what is your perspective

01:07:37.990 --> 01:07:40.870
on people that choose to use a
plural pronoun such as "they"

01:07:40.870 --> 01:07:43.930
or "them" since,
evolutionary speaking,

01:07:43.930 --> 01:07:45.430
they're born female or male?

01:07:45.430 --> 01:07:46.180
GAD SAAD: Right.

01:07:46.180 --> 01:07:48.270
So I recently gave a--

01:07:48.270 --> 01:07:50.770
for those of you who are not
familiar with the question that

01:07:50.770 --> 01:07:51.790
was just posed--

01:07:51.790 --> 01:07:54.160
this is really sort of
a big issue in Canada

01:07:54.160 --> 01:07:57.730
right now because there
is a bill that was just

01:07:57.730 --> 01:08:00.850
tabled and passed
called Bill C-16

01:08:00.850 --> 01:08:03.400
which incorporates gender
identity and gender

01:08:03.400 --> 01:08:06.800
expression as part of
the rubric of hate crime.

01:08:06.800 --> 01:08:10.600
So in other words, if you do
or say or not say or not do

01:08:10.600 --> 01:08:12.520
something, that
could be construed

01:08:12.520 --> 01:08:15.340
as hateful towards
say the transgendered,

01:08:15.340 --> 01:08:18.670
then you could be
liable for a hate crime.

01:08:18.670 --> 01:08:21.430
And to the context of your
specific question of gender

01:08:21.430 --> 01:08:25.149
pronouns, a good friend
of mine and a colleague

01:08:25.149 --> 01:08:29.740
by name of Jordan Peterson
got into a lot of hot waters

01:08:29.740 --> 01:08:30.949
because he said--

01:08:30.949 --> 01:08:33.340
and he's a very
accomplished scientist.

01:08:33.340 --> 01:08:35.649
He's a tenured professor at
the University of Toronto

01:08:35.649 --> 01:08:39.040
in psychology-- he said
you cannot force me,

01:08:39.040 --> 01:08:42.279
the government can't force
me, cannot compel me,

01:08:42.279 --> 01:08:47.524
to use specific pronouns
like zir and ze and so on.

01:08:47.524 --> 01:08:49.399
So I appeared in front
of the Canadian Senate

01:08:49.399 --> 01:08:52.479
and I testified
regarding that issue.

01:08:52.479 --> 01:08:58.250
My position is there's a
huge panoply of personhoods.

01:08:58.250 --> 01:09:00.840
Transgendered people exist,
the non-gendered exist,

01:09:00.840 --> 01:09:02.420
the non-binary exists.

01:09:02.420 --> 01:09:05.270
We should honor everyone.

01:09:05.270 --> 01:09:07.700
We should treat everybody
equal under the law.

01:09:07.700 --> 01:09:09.410
That doesn't mean,
though, that I

01:09:09.410 --> 01:09:12.710
have to celebrate your
personhood by you compelling

01:09:12.710 --> 01:09:16.160
me to come up with pronouns
that are nonsensical.

01:09:16.160 --> 01:09:19.399
So my personal
position is that we're

01:09:19.399 --> 01:09:21.859
threading on dangerous
waters with this bill.

01:09:21.859 --> 01:09:24.180
My point during the
Senate hearing by the way,

01:09:24.180 --> 01:09:27.050
was every single
word that I uttered

01:09:27.050 --> 01:09:30.050
in today's lecture
could be construed

01:09:30.050 --> 01:09:32.318
as a transgression of Bill C-16.

01:09:32.318 --> 01:09:34.609
Because when I'm talking,
for example, about innate sex

01:09:34.609 --> 01:09:37.609
differences, someone could
raise their hand and say,

01:09:37.609 --> 01:09:41.180
never in your course did you
mention the transgendered

01:09:41.180 --> 01:09:43.850
or the non-gendered
or the non-binary,

01:09:43.850 --> 01:09:45.439
and that marginalizes me.

01:09:45.439 --> 01:09:47.660
So literally,
evolutionary biology

01:09:47.660 --> 01:09:50.029
and evolutionary
psychology could become

01:09:50.029 --> 01:09:51.859
transgressive of this bill.

01:09:51.859 --> 01:09:55.190
So while I respect
everyone's personhood,

01:09:55.190 --> 01:09:59.490
that doesn't mean that it
should be anti-science.

01:09:59.490 --> 01:10:00.777
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:10:00.777 --> 01:10:02.860
JORDAN THIBODEAU: You can
have a seat if you want.

01:10:02.860 --> 01:10:04.860
GAD SAAD: It's hard for
me to sit on this thing.

01:10:04.860 --> 01:10:06.090
I feel as though like it's--

01:10:06.090 --> 01:10:08.990
I've got this,
you've got nothing.

01:10:08.990 --> 01:10:11.370
Now it's forever on Google.

01:10:11.370 --> 01:10:14.130
JORDAN THIBODEAU: It's because
I'm sucking it in actually.

01:10:14.130 --> 01:10:17.460
Your book is critical
religion and what

01:10:17.460 --> 01:10:20.670
are the positive psychological
aspects of religion?

01:10:20.670 --> 01:10:22.290
GAD SAAD: Yes, great question.

01:10:22.290 --> 01:10:25.830
So in in chapter 8 of my book--
for those of you who took

01:10:25.830 --> 01:10:30.510
a copy, the chapter is titled
"marketing hope by selling

01:10:30.510 --> 01:10:31.350
lies"--

01:10:31.350 --> 01:10:34.560
so that might give
you a general summary

01:10:34.560 --> 01:10:37.770
of what I think of religion.

01:10:37.770 --> 01:10:39.600
It's very hard to
eradicate religion

01:10:39.600 --> 01:10:43.200
because, ultimately,
we are the only being

01:10:43.200 --> 01:10:46.530
that we are aware of that
is aware of its mortality.

01:10:46.530 --> 01:10:50.430
And to the extent that we suffer
from this existential angst,

01:10:50.430 --> 01:10:53.910
our only solution to
that is to subscribe

01:10:53.910 --> 01:10:56.100
to some religious narrative.

01:10:56.100 --> 01:10:58.740
Because all religious
narratives ultimately

01:10:58.740 --> 01:11:02.520
offer you a solution,
quote, "to this problem."

01:11:02.520 --> 01:11:04.680
But here I'm torn,
because on the one hand,

01:11:04.680 --> 01:11:07.860
I appreciate the fact that
religion has some functional

01:11:07.860 --> 01:11:08.940
benefits.

01:11:08.940 --> 01:11:13.840
But on the other hand, if you
truly wish to pursue truth,

01:11:13.840 --> 01:11:16.690
then maybe believing
in wrong ideas,

01:11:16.690 --> 01:11:18.880
even though they
feel good, might not

01:11:18.880 --> 01:11:22.780
be a good thing to do.

01:11:22.780 --> 01:11:27.510
So I guess my thinking is few
people have the testicular

01:11:27.510 --> 01:11:30.840
fortitude to be
nonbelievers because it's

01:11:30.840 --> 01:11:34.165
a lot easier to be a believer.

01:11:34.165 --> 01:11:36.290
JORDAN THIBODEAU: What's
the most exciting frontier

01:11:36.290 --> 01:11:38.620
of evolutionary
psychology for you?

01:11:38.620 --> 01:11:40.530
GAD SAAD: Oh great question.

01:11:40.530 --> 01:11:42.900
I think it is to
apply the principles

01:11:42.900 --> 01:11:45.720
of evolutionary psychology
in practical fields.

01:11:45.720 --> 01:11:47.610
So for example, in
my case, I apply it

01:11:47.610 --> 01:11:50.250
in consumer behavior
in business.

01:11:50.250 --> 01:11:54.480
Now there is the application
of evolutionary theory

01:11:54.480 --> 01:11:55.130
in medicine.

01:11:55.130 --> 01:11:57.588
Now you might think, oh, but
hasn't that been done already?

01:11:57.588 --> 01:11:58.110
No.

01:11:58.110 --> 01:12:02.520
Most physicians will never
hear the word evolution ever

01:12:02.520 --> 01:12:05.550
uttered because they work
at the proximate level.

01:12:05.550 --> 01:12:08.192
My good colleague who was, by
the way, a guest on my show,

01:12:08.192 --> 01:12:10.650
Randy Nesse, one of the pioneers
of evolution and medicine.

01:12:10.650 --> 01:12:13.560
And is now trying
to make it part

01:12:13.560 --> 01:12:15.810
of the curriculum
of medical school

01:12:15.810 --> 01:12:17.664
that physicians,
future physicians,

01:12:17.664 --> 01:12:19.080
be trained in
evolutionary theory,

01:12:19.080 --> 01:12:20.579
because there are
insights that come

01:12:20.579 --> 01:12:23.490
from evolutionary principles
that you would typically not

01:12:23.490 --> 01:12:26.230
have access to if you
didn't have that lens.

01:12:26.230 --> 01:12:28.950
There's a field now
called evolutionary law

01:12:28.950 --> 01:12:32.490
where you apply principles
from evolutionary theory

01:12:32.490 --> 01:12:34.710
to understand whether
legal codes are

01:12:34.710 --> 01:12:36.510
consistent with
human nature or not.

01:12:36.510 --> 01:12:39.480
So I think the next
frontier is to move

01:12:39.480 --> 01:12:42.270
beyond the study of
mating behavior and so on.

01:12:42.270 --> 01:12:46.050
It's to take the key of
evolutionary psychology

01:12:46.050 --> 01:12:49.347
and use it to unlock
different practical fields.

01:12:49.347 --> 01:12:51.680
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Going back
to you comment on the car--

