01:13:47.180 --> 01:13:48.846
people will honk right
away because it's

01:13:48.846 --> 01:13:51.210
like, who is this person?

01:13:51.210 --> 01:13:53.840
But I wanted to ask
you, you had a point

01:13:53.840 --> 01:13:57.176
about how birth order affects
our psychology in families.

01:13:57.176 --> 01:13:58.550
Can you talk a
little about that?

01:13:58.550 --> 01:14:00.877
GAD SAAD: Sure.

01:14:00.877 --> 01:14:03.210
There's this gentleman by the
name of Frank Sulloway who

01:14:03.210 --> 01:14:05.450
is a historian of science
and a Darwinists who

01:14:05.450 --> 01:14:10.130
came up with an incredible idea
to explain birth order effect.

01:14:10.130 --> 01:14:12.380
Typically, when you
talk about birth order--

01:14:12.380 --> 01:14:14.797
sorry, should I be looking at
you or is it OK to look at--

01:14:14.797 --> 01:14:15.921
JORDAN THIBODEAU: Everyone.

01:14:15.921 --> 01:14:16.607
Yeah.

01:14:16.607 --> 01:14:17.815
I know I'm just too handsome.

01:14:17.815 --> 01:14:18.460
It's hard.

01:14:21.170 --> 01:14:23.570
GAD SAAD: Typically, when you
study birth order effects,

01:14:23.570 --> 01:14:24.986
it is studied from
the perspective

01:14:24.986 --> 01:14:30.800
of how parents treat children
of different orders differently.

01:14:30.800 --> 01:14:33.080
So they might treat the
firstborn differently

01:14:33.080 --> 01:14:35.690
than the last born,
and that's the genesis

01:14:35.690 --> 01:14:38.390
of birth order phenomenon.

01:14:38.390 --> 01:14:41.360
Frank Sulloway flipped that
whole script upside down.

01:14:41.360 --> 01:14:44.060
He argued that
no, actually, what

01:14:44.060 --> 01:14:47.410
drives birth order effects
are the children themselves.

01:14:47.410 --> 01:14:49.160
And let me just explain
that very quickly.

01:14:49.160 --> 01:14:51.320
It's actually an interesting
marketing problem.

01:14:51.320 --> 01:14:54.170
The fancy term is
called Darwinian niche

01:14:54.170 --> 01:14:55.430
partitioning hypothesis.

01:14:55.430 --> 01:14:57.150
So it basically
works as follows.

01:14:57.150 --> 01:14:59.720
When a child is
born, one of the ways

01:14:59.720 --> 01:15:04.100
that it has to secure
maximal parental investment

01:15:04.100 --> 01:15:06.200
is to convince the
parents that it

01:15:06.200 --> 01:15:09.470
is uniquely different from
all the other children.

01:15:09.470 --> 01:15:11.300
So there are many
different niches

01:15:11.300 --> 01:15:13.850
I could occupy as a child.

01:15:13.850 --> 01:15:15.110
I could be the good boy.

01:15:15.110 --> 01:15:16.690
I could be the rebellious boy.

01:15:16.690 --> 01:15:20.900
So if I'm the first born, all
of the niches are unoccupied.

01:15:20.900 --> 01:15:21.540
Correct?

01:15:21.540 --> 01:15:23.090
Therefore, I could
pick any of them.

01:15:23.090 --> 01:15:26.030
If I'm the second born,
I have n minus niches.

01:15:26.030 --> 01:15:30.360
As I go down the sip ship,
there are fewer and fewer niches

01:15:30.360 --> 01:15:33.290
from which I could fill.

01:15:33.290 --> 01:15:38.180
And he argued that
that adaptive problem

01:15:38.180 --> 01:15:42.050
causes later-borns
to score higher

01:15:42.050 --> 01:15:45.830
on openness to experiences,
to be greater thinkers

01:15:45.830 --> 01:15:49.040
outside the box because
of this original problem

01:15:49.040 --> 01:15:50.720
that they have to
solve, which is

01:15:50.720 --> 01:15:53.810
how could I be maximally
different from all

01:15:53.810 --> 01:15:55.190
my other siblings?

01:15:55.190 --> 01:15:56.720
And whenever I
lecture about this,

01:15:56.720 --> 01:15:58.820
I always end with
the following-- can

01:15:58.820 --> 01:16:03.394
we guess what professor
Saad's birth order is?

01:16:03.394 --> 01:16:04.870
Boom.

01:16:04.870 --> 01:16:09.160
I was destined for greatness
cause I'm last born.

01:16:09.160 --> 01:16:12.100
I'm the last four.

01:16:12.100 --> 01:16:15.030
So that's the explanation
for the birth order effect.

